{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782397574,"nonce":"lPmnz5jfusH0H3d5r4YUmzTY0q8=","title":"EXTRACT(SECOND) / sub-second date fields","message":"Follow-up from the date/time functions PR (#48, bug 0a8c09e).\n\n`DateField` currently excludes `Second` because the field's semantics diverge across backends:\nPostgreSQL's `EXTRACT(SECOND FROM ts)` is fractional (e.g. 56.789) while MySQL's is an integer (56),\nand the i64-pinning cast would round PG's value (-\u003e 57). The PR deliberately ships Year/Month/Day/\nHour/Minute only (all integers in both backends, so i64 is exactly uniform).\n\nDesign a fractional-aware sub-second story, e.g.:\n- a separate `extract_second()` returning f64 (PG `EXTRACT(SECOND)` is double-ish; MySQL\n  `EXTRACT(MICROSECOND)`/`SECOND` composition), or\n- `DateField::Second` with an explicit FLOOR so it truncates consistently to i64 (matching MySQL),\n  plus `Millisecond`/`Microsecond` fields if useful.\n\nDecide uniform semantics across PostgreSQL and MySQL before re-adding `Second`.","files":null}]}